attributes.title: Gun Policy Lab Experiment
attributes.description:
--This study is a continuation of our gun control study,, osf.io/5gc4t , but this study involves only gun owners in our sample and uses a donation measure as a key behavioral measure--

The goal of this study is to examine under what conditions public consensus about gun policies influence beliefs and actions, particularly those of American gun owners. Specifically, we explore whether public opinion information detailing gun owners’ support for key gun policies can influence gun owners' expression of support for these policies. We also examine whether public opinion information is most effective when gun owners perceive gun policy can be changed.

q2.value:
H1: Informing that a majority of gun owners support key gun policies results in gun owners reporting: higher estimates of gun owner support, perceiving gun policies as more effective at reducing gun violence, reporting greater willingness to publicly express support for policies, perceiving gun policies as more urgent, and expressing a lesser willingness to use deception when publicly expressing views of gun policies.

H2: Informing that a majority of gun owners support key gun policies results in greater private and public expression of gun policy support.

H3:  Informing that a majority of gun owners support key gun policies results in greater donations to a gun control organization.


H4a: The presence of system change information will moderate the effect of consensus information on public/private support, donations, perceived effectiveness, and perceived urgency. 

H4b: When consensus information includes system change information, it will be most effective at influencing public/private expressions of support, donations, perceived effectiveness, and perceived urgency.

q3.value: Experiment - A researcher randomly assigns treatments to study subjects, this includes field or lab experiments. This is also known as an intervention experiment and includes randomized controlled trials.

value: Personnel who interact directly with the study subjects (either human or non-human subjects) will not be aware of the assigned treatments. (Commonly known as “double blind”)

question.value: The proposed study will be a 2 (consensus statement versus no consensus statement) X 2 (system changeable versus no system changeable) lab experiment. Each participant will be presented with a short statement about the recent school shooting at Marjory Stoneman Douglas High School in 2018. Our “changeable” manipulation will describe how in the aftermath of the shooting, Florida’s state legislature passed bipartisan legislation that strengthened background checks and implemented a mandatory waiting period. The “non-changeable” manipulation will mention how the federal government has not made any changes to strengthening background checks and implementing a mandatory waiting period. The “consensus information” manipulation will include statistical polling data showing the percent of gun owners that support universal background checks and mandatory waiting periods. All manipulated content is factual. No deception is being used with this content.

q8.value: Registration prior to creation of data

question.value: Participants will be from a YouGov panel, must be 18 years or older and must be gun owners.  Participants are rewarded $20, of which they can donate some or all to The Sandy Hook Promise.

Our key self-report outcome variables will be: (1) perceived policy urgency, (2) perceived policy effectiveness, (3) willingness to publicly share views on gun policies, (4) difference in public versus private expression of policy views.

We also include manipulation checks that ensure our system change manipulation elicits perceptions of system change, and that our consensus information does impact perceived consensus on gun policies.

Following the end of the study, participants will be told they are awarded $20 for completing the study of which they can donate some or all to the Sandy Hook Promise, a gun violence advocacy organization. The amount donated is treated as a key dependent variable. Participants will also be asked if they would like to sign a petition that urge government officials to pass legislation on universal background checks. Their response or omission will be treated as a key outcome measure.
Data will be analyzed using statistical programs such as SPSS. Appropriate statistical analyses (e.g. regression models, ANOVAs, Chi Squared) will be employed to examine the effects.

attributes.title: Filsafat Socrates Dan Latar Belakang Munculnya Kaum Sofis
attributes.description: socrates menjadi hal yang begitu pelik bagi para sejarawan. pasalnya banyak yang mengungkapkan banyak hal tentang socrates. Namun tidak semua ungakapan itu benar adanya, pasalnya para sejarawan hanya bisa mengetahui seluk beluk socrates dari para muridnya, itupun tidak pasti apakah mengetahui banyak tentangnya ataupun hanya mengetahui sebagian saja. socrates hidup satu zaman dengan kaum sofis. socrates tidak meninggalkan sedikitpun karyanya, karena memang dia bukan berfilsafat untuk hidup, namun dia hidup berfilsafat. dia menghabiskan waktu untuk mengajar para remaja, namun tidak seperti kaum sofis yang mengajar untuk mencari uang. dia mengajar untuk mengajarkan sebuah kebenaran dari kebenaran.

attributes.title: Predicting the endorsement of preventive behaviors in the context of the Corona virus pandemic
attributes.description: The current situation of the ongoing new Corona virus pandemic offers a rare chance to investigate the relation between perceived risks for oneself and one’s social environment, known health-behavior related factors (i.e., self-efficacy, response efficacy of different preventive behaviors, perceived social norms), and the self-reported intention and adoption of protective behaviors. We will investigate the associations in risk perception, health-behavior related factors, and self-reported preventive behaviors in a representative sample of the Swiss population.

q2.value:
1. Higher perceived risk to self of (1) contracting Covid-19, (2) developing severe symptoms, and (3) spreading the virus is related to (i) higher intentions to adopt and (ii) higher endorsement of (a) preventive behaviors, (b) social distancing, (c) recommended behaviors in case of symptoms, and (d) alternative measures (measures that are known to be ineffective).

2. Higher perceived risk to self of (1) contracting Covid-19, and of (2) developing severe symptoms is related to higher worries for contracting the virus oneself.

3. Higher perceived risk to self of spreading the virus and higher perceived risk to others of (1) contracting Covid-19, and of (2) developing severe symptoms are related to worries for others contracting the virus.

4. Higher perceived risk to others of (1) contracting Covid-19, (2) developing severe symptoms, and (3) spreading the virus is related to (i) higher intentions to adopt and (ii) higher endorsement of (a) preventive behaviors, (b) social distancing, (c) recommended behaviors in case of symptoms, and (d) alternative measures (measures that are known to be ineffective).

5. Higher self-efficacy of engaging in (a) preventive behaviors, (b) social distancing, (c) recommended behaviors in case of symptoms are related to (i) higher intentions to adopt (a), (b), and (c), respectively, and (ii) higher self-reported adherence to (a), (b),and (c), respectively. 

6. Self-efficacy is assumed to moderate the associations between risk perceptions and intention and behavior: The positive associations as specified in Hypotheses 1 and 4 are stronger when self-efficacy for the different behaviors is higher and weaker when self-efficacy for the different behaviors is lower.

7. Higher response efficacy, i.e., the perceived effectiveness of engaging in (a) preventive behaviors, (b) social distancing, (c) recommended behaviors in case of symptoms, and (d) alternative measures (measures that are known to be ineffective) are related to (i) higher intentions to adopt (a), (b), (c), and (d), respectively, and (ii) higher self-reported adherence to (a), (b),(c), and (d), respectively. 

8. Higher intentions to adopt (a) preventive behaviors, (b) social distancing, (c) recommended behaviors in case of symptoms, and (d) alternative measures (measures that are known to be ineffective) are related to higher levels in these behaviors (self-reported frequency).

9. More information seeking about the virus is related to (i) higher intentions to adopt and (ii) higher self-reported adherence to (a) preventive behaviors, (b) social distancing, (c) recommended behaviors in case of symptoms, respectively, and (iii) lower intentions to adopt and (iii) lower self-reported adherence to (d) alternative measures (measures that are known to be ineffective). 

10. Higher trust in authorities during the pandemic (i.e., the politics, the health system, the media) is related to (i) higher intentions to adopt and (ii) higher self-reported adherence to (a) preventive behaviors, (b) social distancing, (c) recommended behaviors in case of symptoms, respectively, and (iii) lower intentions to adopt and (iii) lower self-reported adherence to (d) alternative measures (measures that are known to be ineffective).

11. Higher prosocial orientation is related to (i) higher intentions to adopt (a) preventive behaviors, (b) social distancing, (c) recommended behaviors in case of symptoms, and (d) alternative measures (measures that are known to be ineffective) respectively, and (ii) higher self-reported adherence to (a), (b),(c), and (d), respectively.

12. Prosocial orientation increases with age.

13. Perceived social norms (i.e., disapproval of adopting (a) preventive behaviors, (b) social distancing, (c) recommended behaviors in case of symptoms, and (d) alternative measures (measures that are known to be ineffective)) are negatively related to (i) intentions to adopt  (a), (b), (c), and (d), respectively, and (ii) to engaging in (a), (b),(c), and (d), respectively.
 
14. Moderation hypothesis with age as moderator
(a) Younger adults are less likely than older adults to perceive the risk they pose to transmitting the new Corona virus and the resulting potential harm to others. 
(b) The lower perceived other-related risk, in turn, is hypothesized to lower the likelihood of adopting social distancing behaviors. 

In addition to these theoretically derived hypotheses, we will explore differences between various groups (e.g., regional groups, gender), regarding mean differences in the central variables assessed in this study as well as differences in the above specified hypotheses.

q3.value: Observational Study - Data is collected from study subjects that are not randomly assigned to a treatment. This includes surveys, “natural experiments,” and regression discontinuity designs.

value: No blinding is involved in this study.

question.value:
This study is cross-sectional with one representative survey taking place end of March 2020. 
A longitudinal study with eight monthly points of measurement is planned and depends on requested funding. All participants included in the first survey will be asked to continue their participation in the following surveys.

q8.value: Registration prior to creation of data

question.value:
For data collection, we collaborate with gfs Zürich. Random digit dialing (RDD) will be implemented to allow inclusion of households not listed in the telephone book and of mobile phone numbers and younger people who oftentimes do not have landline networks anymore. The survey will be run by telephone. 
In case of funding of additional longitudinal points of measurement, all participants included in the first survey will be offered to complete the following surveys online.

q11.value: We sample 1000 cohabitants of Switzerland: 200 people living in the Italian speaking part, 300 people living in the French speaking part, and 500 adults living in the German speaking part of Switzerland. New participants will be recruited in every wave for compensating dropouts.

question.value: The attached file contains the constructs assessed in this study.

Cross-sectional data will be analyzed (a) descriptively characterizing the Swiss population regarding the variables assessed in this study, and (b) examining the hypotheses using general linear modeling approaches. Data will be weighted in order to account for biases and allow representation of the population.

Exploratory analyses comparing groups regarding mean differences in the variables assessed in this study or potential moderations will be analyzed using Bayesian statistics as no hypotheses are specified. 

In case of successful funding, longitudinal data will be analyzed using latent growth models and multilevel models.

data.value: No, no data have been collected for this study yet.

other.value: Although our main prediction is for a main effect, rather than an interaction, previous research addressing the same hypothesis found a condition*germ aversion moderation effect. We plan to run exploratory bootstrapped regression analyses to test for this effect. using the Perceived Vulnerability to Disease Questionnaire (Duncan, Schaller, Park, 2009). Mean composites for the Germ Aversion and Perceived Infectability subscales

sample.value: 750 participants from Cloud Research via MTurk will be utilized. Participants will be prepaid, so data collection will stop automatically when this number of participants have submitted.

analyses.value:
A one-way, three condition ANOVA will be conducted to assess if those who in the virus condition have higher scores on the short-term mating orientation measure than participants in the other two conditions. 


To test the relationship between germ aversion and sociosexuality, we will initially run a bivariate correlation analysis. We will then run a multiple regression including germ aversion, sex, age, and relationship status (dichotomized as single or in a relationship) as predictors.

outliers.value:
Outliers: If an individual’s score for the dependent variable are more than 3 standard deviations above or below the mean, they will be winsorized.

Exclusion
1. If anyone puts a 4 or lower in the honesty check (which directly asks participants if they were honest during the survey) their data will not be used in the analysis.
2. If participants do not answer the written part of the prime, if the answer is not in coherent English, or if the participants did not follow instructions correctly in their written answer.

dependent.value:
To measure sociosexuality, we will use an adapted version of the Sociosexuality Orientation Inventory (SOI-R, Penke & Asendorpf, 2008). We have made some changes to the original scale, because we are more interested in people’s future intentions than in their past behavior (since past behavior cannot be changed with an experimental manipulation). Thus, we have removed and modified some items. The adapted 9-item version is below.

Answers to each item will be z-scored, and the average z-score across all items will give the overall score. All items are listed below.

Sociosexuality

Desire and Attitude Facets will stay the same as in the original version. The behavioral items have been modified to assess future behavior, as below:

Behavioral (0 1 2 3 4 5-6 7-9 10-19 20 or more)
 1. How many sexual partners would you like to have in the next 12 months?
 2. With how many one-night stands would you like to have in the course of the next year?
 3. With how many one-night stands would you like to have in the course of the next 10 years?

conditions.value:
There will be three different conditions for the current experiment. 

Participants will be randomized into either Disease-threat, Accident or Control condition (See the survey for the prime). After they read the prime, they will be asked to “Take a moment to reflect on how this information made you feel. Please briefly write about your reactions to the information.  What kind of world did the information describe? What details stood out to you most when reading? How did you feel as you read the story? You have up to two minutes for this task, after which the next arrow will appear.”  After they respond they will be asked to report 2 specific pieces of information from the prime.” 

The control condition which will not receive anything will not be tasked to enter that information

hypothesis.value:
At the time of the study, there are widespread concerns about the Coronavirus. We are interested in testing the effects of concerns about a real-life disease threat on social and sexual attitudes. We predict that reminding people about the dangers of the Coronavirus (the disease-threat condition), will lead to more restricted sociosexual attitudes.

1.	Participants in the disease-threat condition will have lower scores on a measure of sociosexuality (indicating restricted attitudes to sexuality) than participants in a control condition or in a non-disease threat condition (which informs participants about the risks of death and injury from home accidents). Restricted sexual attitudes indicate that those individuals hold less favorable attitudes and desire towards promiscuous sexual behavior.

2. Germ aversion will be negatively associated with sociosexuality.

attributes.title: Effectiveness of dry needling for lateral elbow tendinopathy
attributes.description: Epicondylalgia, also known as epicondylitis, epicondylosis, lateral elbow pain, lateral elbow tendinopathy or tennis elbow, is a common upper arm painful condition. Epicondylalgia is pain in the lateral epicondyle of the humerus or in the tendons or muscles originating from it. The condition usually arises from resisted use of the extensor muscles of the wrist and can be associated with occupational tasks or sports  which require forceful and/or repetitive activity. Overall the economic burden of epicondylalgia is high resulting in significant loss of work days and reduced work capacity.

q2.value: Dry needling (without drugs) are effective for the treatment of the lateral elbow tendinopathy

q3.value: Meta-Analysis - A systematic review of published studies.

value: No blinding is involved in this study.

question.value: A systematic review and meta-analysis included parallel or cross-over randomized clinical trials that used  dry needling alone or in combination with other treatments in comparison with other group or control

q8.value: Registration prior to creation of data

question.value: Participants must be al least 18 years old with lateral elbow tendinopathy diagnosed through common physical test or ultrasound imaging treated with any modalities of dry needling. Also, the included studies will be randomized clinical trials with at least one group that used a needle intervention alone or in combination with other therapy and a comparative group (other intervention or control group).

q11.value: We will analyze all studies that we can include in the systematic review and meta-analysis

question.value: Efficacy outcomes like intensity of pain (for example numeric rating scale of pain or visual analogue scale), function/disability (for example PRTEE questionnaire or DASH questionnaire) hand-grip strength (for example maximal voluntary contraction of hand-drip or free pain hand grip strength) or pain sensitivity (for example pressure pain threshold)

We will use Review Manager 5.3 software to statistically analyze data. If there is homogeneity between the studies we will use a fixed effect model, otherwise, a random effects model will be applied.

Heterogeneity and inconsistency will be assessed through the inspection of a forest plot, and I² test, and based on the criteria of each study.

Furthermore we will use the funnel plot to check the potential publication bias.

If we have sufficient data, we will conduct subgroup analyses according to the mean period of follow-up and needle interventions.

q23.value:
Two independent authors will screen both the titles and abstracts of the references retrieved during the searches, after which full text screening will be carried out in accordance with the inclusion and exclusion criteria.

Data extraction will also be carried out by two independent authors, and data including title, author, published date, study design, and other data concerning our research questions will be collected. For all steps, any disagreements will be resolved by a third author, if required.

The risk of bias assessment will be carried out by two or more authors in accordance with the recommendations set out in the Cochrane Handbook for Systematic Reviews of Interventions, including following items: sequence generation, allocation concealment, blinding of participants, personnel and outcome assessors, incomplete outcome data, selective outcome reporting, and other sources of bias. We will grade each item as “low risk”, “high risk”, or “unclear”. Disagreements will be discussed with another reviewer. Also the PEDro score was performed to evaluate the metohodological quality

name.value: Moral outrage in times of Corona: Bad or uninformed citizens?

other.value: We will also explore how people’s opinions changed before and after the rules were enforced. If we collect sufficient data we might also examine whether the findings differ for different demographic groups (age, gender, education level, country). Depending on the response rate, we might also decide to test for time of testing (e.g., first two weeks after study launch vs last two weeks).

sample.value: Minimal sample size is 100. We will promote the study on social media and hope to recruit as many participants as possible. We will not analyze the data if we manage to recruit fewer than 100 participants.

analyses.value: We will examine correlations among the four ratings.

dependent.value:
We ask participants four questions:
1. To what extent do you feel that violating social distancing rules is morally condemnable (i.e., how "wrong" is such behavior)? 
2. How likely do you think it is that you will get Corona if you don't respect social distancing rules? 
3. How likely do you think it is that you will infect somebody else if you don't respect social distancing rules? 
4. To what extent do you respect social distancing yourself?

conditions.value: Participants are asked to solve the four questions twice. First, we ask them about their current opinion (after social distancing rules have been enforced). Next, we ask them to give their past opinion at the time social distancing rules were not yet enforced.

hypothesis.value: We are interested in people's moral response to the Corona crisis. A lot of people strongly condemn others who do not respect social distancing rules. We want to test whether this is driven by the fact that these people  have higher moral standards or are simply better informed about the risk of contagion. Key question is whether we all have similar beliefs about the risk of contagion but simply differ in how much we are inclined to respect the distancing rules or whether differences in inclination to respect the rules is driven by people's beliefs about the risk of contagion?

attributes.title: Pathways linking parental health literacy (HL) with health behaviours directed at the child: a scoping review.
attributes.description: The aim of the scoping review is to identify and to comprehensively describe the variety of pathways between parental health literacy (HL) and health behaviours directed at the child which were empirically tested in previous studies.

attributes.title: Network perception
attributes.description: This study is to test how people perceived different network structure jointly with the focal actor's gender, then determines their social perceptions towards the focal actor.

data.value: No, no data have been collected for this study yet.

analyses.value:
2 (target with a high-status vs. low-status network) x 2 (target is a woman vs. a man) ANOVA analysis on the dependent variables. 
Mean differences comparisons between high-status vs. low-status network within different focal actor's gender conditions
Mean differences comparisons between woman vs. man within different network status conditions
Indirect effects on 1) whether network status and gender jointly predict perceived communality then status conferral; 2) whether network status induced assertiveness perceived interacts with gender predicts perceived communality and status conferral.

outliers.value: Non-US participants will be excluded; participants failed the manipulation check will be excluded.

dependent.value: Status conferral (e.g., "I respect that person"; Lount & Pettit, 2012; Pettit, Yong, & Spataro, 2010), perceived assertiveness (e.g., "assertive", "dominant", etc.), commonality (e.g., "generous", "warm"), and competence (e.g., "competent", "skillful"; Eagly & Steffen, 1984; Fiske et al., 1999).

conditions.value:
This study features a 2 (target with a high-status vs. low-status network) x 2 (target is a woman vs. a man) between-subject design. Participants will be assigned randomly to one out of the 4 conditions. 

Participants in each condition will be assigned a scenario, which describes a person in a company and the composition of his/her network. In the high- (low-) status network conditions, the focal person mainly connects with high-status (low-status) alters. And the focal person's gender was manipulated by his/her name.

hypothesis.value: I hypothesize that observers will perceive a target with a high-status network as higher in assertiveness, such perception will further be perceived as lowered communality if the target is a woman (but not a man) then shape the observers' status conferral towards the target.
